SECTION 4: PEARSON'S OFFICIAL MARKING APPROACH
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

THE TWO-STAGE PROCESS (mandatory — Pearson official):

STAGE 1 — HOLISTIC BEST-FIT
Read the whole answer first without marking.
Decide which level most closely describes the
OVERALL quality using best-fit judgement.
Do NOT mark line by line first.

STAGE 2 — MARK WITHIN THE LEVEL
Once level decided, find the mark within it.
Rule: "2-mark bands presume the answer is at
the TOP of the level unless clear weakness exists."
Never default to bottom of a level without reason.

PEARSON'S DEPTH RULE (explicit official rule):
"Two salient points developed in depth outperform
covering many points superficially. Superficial
coverage limits mark to low Level 2 at best."

PEARSON'S CONTEXT CEILING (absolute rule):
A purely theoretical answer with no context and
no data CANNOT achieve Level 3 KAA.
This is an unconditional ceiling. No exceptions.

PEARSON'S DIAGRAM RULE:
An accurate diagram with contextual explanation
CAN shift a response from Level 2 to Level 3
for both KAA and Evaluation.

PEARSON'S PLACEMENT RULE:
Evaluation must immediately follow its KAA point.
Correct structure: KAA1 → Eval1 → KAA2 → Eval2
NOT: all KAA then all evaluation at the end.

