CALIBRATION ANCHOR 1 — GRADE U (Q13 essay, ~4/20)
"Government spending on infrastructure is good for
the economy because it creates jobs. Workers then
spend money which helps other businesses. This is
good for China which spent money on infrastructure.
However it could cause inflation. Overall the
benefits outweigh the costs."
CONFIRMED MARK: KAA 3/12 (Level 1) + Eval 1/8
(Level 1) = 4/20
WHY: No chains. Generic. No data. Listing judgement.

CALIBRATION ANCHOR 2 — GRADE E (Q13 essay, ~8/20)
"An increase in government expenditure on
infrastructure increases AD as government spending
(G) is a component of AD (C+I+G+X-M). This shifts
AD rightward causing real output to rise. This
reduces unemployment. In China the government spent
1.48 trillion yuan on infrastructure.
However this could cause inflation as prices rise
when AD increases. There is also a time lag before
projects are completed."
CONFIRMED MARK: KAA 5/12 (Level 2) + Eval 3/8
(Level 2) = 8/20
WHY: Two-stage chains only. Country named with data
but not integrated. Evaluation present but generic
and not conditional.

CALIBRATION ANCHOR 3 — GRADE C (Q13 essay, ~12/20)
"Infrastructure spending refers to government
investment in transport, energy and telecommunications.
This increases G, a component of AD (C+I+G+X-M),
so AD shifts rightward from AD1 to AD2, causing real
output to rise from Y1 to Y2 and unemployment to
fall as firms hire more workers for construction
projects. The multiplier effect then amplifies this
initial injection — in China, the 1.48 trillion yuan
investment would generate further rounds of spending
as workers earn and consume more.
However the magnitude of the multiplier depends on
MPW — if MPW is high, the multiplier 1/MPW is small,
limiting the impact on real output. This means the
1.48 trillion yuan may have a more limited effect
than expected.
In the long run, infrastructure lowers production
costs for firms, shifting LRAS rightward and
increasing productive capacity.
However there is a significant time lag before
projects are completed, meaning short-run disruption
may outweigh immediate benefits."
CONFIRMED MARK: KAA 8/12 (Level 3) + Eval 4/8
(Level 2) = 12/20
WHY: 3-stage chains. Country data integrated.
Two KAA points developed. Evaluation partially
developed but judgement not conditional.

CALIBRATION ANCHOR 4 — GRADE A (Q13 essay, ~17/20)
"Infrastructure refers to the basic physical and
organisational structures needed for the operation
of a society, including transport, energy and
telecommunications networks. In China, the
government's 1.48 trillion yuan infrastructure
investment in 2022 provides a strong context for
evaluating these benefits.

In the short run, this expenditure increases G,
a component of AD (C+I+G+X-M), so AD shifts
rightward from AD1 to AD2 causing real output to
rise from Y1 to Y2 as shown in diagram 1. This
fall in cyclical unemployment creates income for
workers who then increase consumption (C), shifting
AD further right through the multiplier effect —
assuming China's relatively high MPC, this
multiplier could amplify the 1.48 trillion yuan
injection significantly into the broader economy.

However, the impact on real output depends critically
on the level of spare capacity in China's economy.
If China is operating near its productive capacity,
the rightward AD shift will primarily cause
inflationary pressure rather than real output
growth, undermining the intended benefit. The
effectiveness is therefore conditional on the
output gap at the time of spending.

In the long run, improved transport networks reduce
production costs for Chinese firms — raw materials
move more efficiently, workers waste less commute
time, and reliable energy prevents production
disruption — so LRAS shifts rightward from LRAS1
to LRAS2, increasing potential output from Yf1 to
Yf2 and enabling non-inflationary growth.

However, infrastructure projects carry significant
time lags — the 1.48 trillion yuan may take 5-10
years before productivity gains materialise,
meaning the long-run LRAS benefit is uncertain
in its timing and magnitude.

On balance, the benefits of China's infrastructure
spending are likely significant given the multiplier
effect and long-run supply-side gains, but the
overall impact on real output is conditional on
whether China has sufficient spare capacity to
absorb the AD increase without inflationary pressure."
CONFIRMED MARK: KAA 11/12 (Level 4) + Eval 6/8
(Level 2/3) = 17/20
WHY: Complete multi-stage chains. Fully integrated
country data. LRAS mechanism fully developed.
Conditional judgement present. Evaluation partially
Level 3 but second evaluation slightly underdeveloped.

CALIBRATION ANCHOR 5 — GRADE A* (Q13 essay, ~19/20)
[Same as Anchor 4 but add after second evaluation:]
"Furthermore, the increase in government spending
may crowd out private investment if financed through
borrowing — higher government borrowing raises
interest rates, increasing the cost of capital for
firms and reducing private investment (I in AD),
potentially offsetting the initial G increase.
This crowding-out effect is particularly relevant
if China's financial markets are sensitive to
government debt levels, making the net impact on
AD ambiguous rather than definitively positive.

On balance, the benefits of China's 1.48 trillion
yuan infrastructure programme are likely to
outweigh the costs in the long run, primarily
through the LRAS channel of permanently lower
production costs — but only if China has
sufficient spare capacity in the short run
to avoid inflationary pressure, and only if the
programme is financed in a way that does not
significantly crowd out private investment."
CONFIRMED MARK: KAA 12/12 (Level 4) + Eval 7/8
(Level 3) = 19/20
WHY: Complete chains throughout. Crowding out
evaluation challenges the main argument. Fully
conditional judgement with two stated conditions.
Both evaluation points challenge rather than add.

