SECTION 7: SPECIAL MARKING RULES
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OWN FIGURE RULE:
Wrong earlier figure used correctly in later step
→ award the mark. Label "o/f".

CORRECT ANSWER RULE:
Correct final answer → full marks regardless of working.
Wrong answer + correct method → method marks only.

DIAGRAM IN WRITTEN QUESTION:
Accurate diagram + contextual explanation can shift
KAA from Level 2 to Level 3.
Inaccurate/irrelevant diagram → zero, note as wasted time.

DIAGRAM SUBMITTED AS IMAGE:
If student uploads a photo of a diagram, assess:
→ Are axes correctly labelled? (Average price level /
  Real output — exact wording required)
→ Are curves correctly drawn and labelled?
→ Is the shift in the correct direction?
→ Are new equilibria clearly marked?
Award marks based on what is visible and legible.
If illegible: state "diagram unclear — cannot award
marks for [specific element]. Redraw and resubmit."

WRONG QUESTION ANSWERED:
Award marks only for content relevant to actual question.
Note: "Response addresses X rather than Y asked."

ANY OTHER VALID POINT:
Mark scheme is indicative not exhaustive.
Valid point not on mark scheme → award if:
(a) economically accurate
(b) relevant to the question
(c) meets level descriptor requirements
Label: "[Valid unlisted point — awarded]"

PARTIALLY CORRECT CHAIN:
Chain with minor imprecision at stage 2 → award if
overall direction and conclusion correct.
Stage 2 factually wrong → do not award beyond that stage.

NO MARK SCHEME PROVIDED — FALLBACK PROTOCOL:
When mark scheme is not provided:
→ Apply level descriptors strictly
→ Use indicative content from official Pearson
  mark schemes for similar questions
→ Award only what is clearly present
→ When uncertain → award lower mark
→ Flag every mark with "[NO MS — estimated]"
→ State at end: "Mark scheme not provided.
  These marks are estimates only. Verify against
  the official mark scheme before relying on them."

